investing in public companies,

00:02:18.670 --> 00:02:22.190
you are transacting in
a global stock market.

00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:25.670
It's very liquid, you can
buy and sell at any time.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:28.640
And I think there's
just a lot of confusion

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:32.435
out there as to what the stock
market really is, and there

00:02:32.435 --> 00:02:34.040
are also very many approaches.

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:36.160
And it's actually
in the interest

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:39.620
of the financial
community and Wall Street

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:41.580
to make it seem
very complicated,

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:45.030
so that you will just
give your money to them

00:02:45.030 --> 00:02:49.420
and think that they're doing
such a great job for you

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:52.470
that they deserve to
get paid a lot of money.

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:55.640
When in reality, it
isn't that complicated.

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:02.380
The stock market is
a beauty contest,

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:06.020
that's really a criticism
that economist John Maynard

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:11.350
Keynes levied on the stock
market, or on Wall Street.

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:17.280
And it's really this idea that
a lot of investors, and even

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:22.380
professional investors,
will choose companies

00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:25.630
based on what they
think other people will

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:27.870
think of those companies.

00:03:27.870 --> 00:03:31.600
So everybody's kind of trying
to play a guessing game, where

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:34.980
basically you're picking
the prettiest face,

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:37.050
or the prettiest
company-- but it's not

00:03:37.050 --> 00:03:39.170
the one you think
is the prettiest,

00:03:39.170 --> 00:03:42.950
it's the one you think others
will think is the prettiest.

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:45.940
And of course, as Keynes
said in this quote,

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:48.550
you can take that to the third
degree, and the fourth degree,

00:03:48.550 --> 00:03:51.720
and so on, and so on, and it
becomes very self-referential.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:58.410
And because a lot of
people invest this way,

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:02.470
this is how the stock market
might act in the short term.

00:04:02.470 --> 00:04:04.460
It's very
unpredictable, everybody

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:06.370
trying to out-guess
everybody else.

00:04:06.370 --> 00:04:08.690
But that's really
not how you can

00:04:08.690 --> 00:04:11.480
be successful in the long term.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:17.670
And by viewing the stock market
as a parimutuel betting system,

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:21.529
we're getting a little bit
closer to the essence of it.

00:04:21.529 --> 00:04:26.480
Because really it's not about
guessing the prettiest face,

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:29.030
or the best company, or
what others will think--

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:33.080
because if there is a company
out there like Google,

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:35.630
that game becomes pretty easy.

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:40.710
What becomes harder is
calibrating that judgment

00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:44.270
versus what you have
to pay to actually buy

00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:46.650
that company in
the stock market.

00:04:46.650 --> 00:04:51.400
So as Warren Buffett's partner
Charlie Munger says here

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.440
in this quote, sometimes
it's just really easy

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:58.420
to see which horse is
most likely to win a race,

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:02.790
but that horse will
have odds that are maybe

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:05.320
three to two, that
pay three to two,

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:11.540
and some other horse
that doesn't look as fast

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:14.180
may have odds of 100 to one.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:16.310
And then it becomes
much more difficult,

00:05:16.310 --> 00:05:20.540
because probabilistically,
the best horse

00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:23.260
isn't going to win
100% of the time.

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:27.020
What if the horse that
has the odds of 100 to one

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:30.560
can win 5% of the time,
or 10% of the time?

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:34.740
It may actually be the better
investment-- or the better bet,

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:36.150
in this case.

00:05:36.150 --> 00:05:39.510
And this quote
from Warren Buffett

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:41.880
kind of fits that paradigm.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:44.830
He says, we simply
attempt to be fearful

00:05:44.830 --> 00:05:48.030
when others are greedy, and
greedy when others are fearful.

00:05:48.030 --> 00:05:50.390
And that really
speaks to those odds.

00:05:50.390 --> 00:05:53.440
Because if you have everybody
in the world believing

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:57.300
that a company will go
bankrupt, the odds on it

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:00.870
may be so great that if it
just doesn't go bankrupt--

00:06:00.870 --> 00:06:03.940
it may still be a
mediocre company--

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:06.470
you could actually do very well.

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:13.730
And then finally we really get
to the essence of the stock

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:16.560
market, and it's just
a conduit to ownership.

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:18.610
So Google would
be a great company

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:21.660
whether it's publicly
traded or not.

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:24.790
It would still have
the cash flow it has,

00:06:24.790 --> 00:06:27.740
it would still have the
customers that it has.

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:29.990
And so you don't
need the stock market

00:06:29.990 --> 00:06:34.900
to make a Google valuable,
or any other company.

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:36.830
And so it's basically
just a place

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:40.660
to buy and sell
stock in companies.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:41.780
And what is stock?

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:45.130
The legal definition
tells you that it's just

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:48.290
a partial ownership
of a corporation.

00:06:49.330 --> 00:06:53.560
That's really what you're buying
when you invest in a stock.

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:56.390
And it may not seem
that way because it's

00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:58.110
so easy to transact online.

00:06:58.110 --> 00:07:00.530
You're just looking
at a stock ticker,

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:04.800
and it's easy to forget that
what you're really buying

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:06.840
is ownership of a
real life business.

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:14.210
And so you'll hear of all
kinds of different strategies,

00:07:14.210 --> 00:07:17.835
or you'll hear of people trying
to invest based on charts.

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:21.000
They'll look at
different bands and try

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.260
to guess when the stock
is breaking out or not.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:26.650
But that's basically
removing yourself

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:29.690
from the essence of
what a stock really is.

00:07:29.690 --> 00:07:31.940
And when you do that,
your chances of success

00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:33.570
go down dramatically.

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:37.120
Because let's say you do
invest based on a chart,

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:38.760
and you lose all your money.

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:40.100
There's no recourse.

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:43.390
You can say, well,
the chart looked good,

00:07:43.390 --> 00:07:45.940
and in every other case
when that happened,

00:07:45.940 --> 00:07:48.070
the stock did go up.

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:51.180
Well, there's no
connection between that

00:07:51.180 --> 00:07:54.926
and what a stock is legally.

00:07:54.926 --> 00:07:57.490
Legally, it's ownership
of a business.

00:07:57.490 --> 00:08:02.950
And so if you invest in a
company, and you're right,

00:08:02.950 --> 00:08:06.730
you can in the worst
case take the recourse

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:10.620
and acquire a
majority of the stock,

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:13.960
kick out the board of directors,
put in your own directors,

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:16.090
your own management
team, and take

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:18.360
full ownership of that company.

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:22.610
So there you are getting to the
essence of what a stock really

00:08:22.610 --> 00:08:23.110
is.

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.300
And if you invest
based on that essence,

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:29.300
you'll be much more
successful, because you're just

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:34.440
as close to the truth
as can possibly be.

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:40.169
I want to talk a little
bit about the mindset

00:08:40.169 --> 00:08:44.330
that you need to have to
be a successful investor.

00:08:44.330 --> 00:08:48.740
So a lot of investors
will think this way,

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:50.245
kind of the small fish mindset.

00:08:51.610 --> 00:08:54.600
Let's say I have
$100,000 to invest.

00:08:54.600 --> 00:09:00.110
Here's a bunch of companies,
and their stock price

00:09:00.110 --> 00:09:01.345
is their market value.

00:09:02.380 --> 00:09:07.960
Market value simply is what it
would take at the current stock

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:09.865
price to buy the whole company.

00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:14.090
And if you have the
small fish mindset,

00:09:14.090 --> 00:09:16.590
you might just
say, well, $100,000

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:20.200
buys a few thousand shares
of any of these companies.

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:23.587
And my $100,000
is insignificant,

00:09:23.587 --> 00:09:29.080
s so it really doesn't move
the needle on these companies,

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:30.210
or the market is a whole.

00:09:31.370 --> 00:09:35.250
And the reason it's the
wrong mindset to adopt

00:09:35.250 --> 00:09:41.350
is because just because
your portfolio may be small,

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:43.910
your role in the market
is not insignificant.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:49.630
Because the market is supposed
to function efficiently

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:52.340
because even small
investors think

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:55.610
about how well is
company A going

00:09:55.610 --> 00:09:57.725
to do, how much do
I have to pay to buy

00:09:57.725 --> 00:09:59.400
it, et cetera, et cetera.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:02.530
So you really need to
think about not the scale

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:06.070
of your portfolio, but
the scale of the companies

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:07.970
you're investing in.

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:12.830
And so here's kind of the
mindset to be, which is really,

00:10:12.830 --> 00:10:15.450
I think, what successful
investors adopt,

00:10:15.450 --> 00:10:17.690
no matter how much
money they're investing.

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:21.010
And it's the same
table as before,

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:23.730
but we're just showing
it in a different way.

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:27.070
By the way, this is
about 10 years old,

00:10:27.070 --> 00:10:31.080
some of these numbers, so
