And you may still decide
that owning all of Toyota

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.430
is the smarter investment,
but at least you'll

00:11:08.430 --> 00:11:13.120
be aware what that
decision implies.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:16.260
You're no longer on this
slide, where you're thinking,

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:19.350
oh, well, I can buy a few
thousand shares of Toyota

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:23.710
or some other company, and it's
kind of all the same thing.

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:27.230
So here you're realizing
what you're really doing.

00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:36.170
And that mentality, to really
think of investing as an owner,

00:11:36.170 --> 00:11:40.170
I think is very much in
line with the legal essence

00:11:40.170 --> 00:11:41.070
of stocks.

00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:49.740
So here's a very busy
chart, and we're not

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:53.180
going to get through
all of it, but there

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:55.170
are few points I'd
like to make here.

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:59.990
So one is all the way on the
left you see idea generation.

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:01.650
And there's so
many different ways

00:12:01.650 --> 00:12:04.800
to find potential
investment ideas.

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:08.490
You may hear it from friends,
on message boards, read

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:09.980
about a company
in the newspaper.

00:12:11.670 --> 00:12:14.430
You could do a
quantitative stock screen,

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:18.860
searching for the cheapest
companies based on some metric.

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:23.480
So idea generation
generally is the easy part.

00:12:23.480 --> 00:12:27.630
And we can overload
ourselves with ideas.

00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:32.360
There's actually about 10,000
publicly traded companies

00:12:32.360 --> 00:12:35.790
in North America
alone, and probably

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.450
20,000 to 30,000
companies worldwide.

00:12:39.470 --> 00:12:41.990
So there's a ton of
companies to choose from.

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:49.790
So where successful investors
really generate their success--

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:52.410
or as they call it
in the industry,

00:12:52.410 --> 00:12:56.580
their alpha or edge-- is really
in assessing the investment

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:57.530
opportunities.

00:12:57.530 --> 00:13:01.330
So I could give everyone
the same potential company

00:13:01.330 --> 00:13:04.800
to invest in, and someone
will say, wow, that's great,

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:05.490
I want to buy.

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:07.640
Someone will say, no way.

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:09.410
And that's really that decision.

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:12.540
If you can get that
decision right,

00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:14.280
you're going to be successful.

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:20.300
So given what we know now
about the right mentality

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:23.430
to think of a business
as an owner, and would

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.940
I want to buy the whole
company if I could,

00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:28.860
let's walk through
this a little bit.

00:13:28.860 --> 00:13:35.430
So a company will
usually have real assets,

00:13:35.430 --> 00:13:38.130
especially if it's
kind of an old school

00:13:38.130 --> 00:13:40.726
company that maybe
has factories.

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:43.710
Let's take a General Motors.

00:13:43.710 --> 00:13:45.820
They've got
factories, they've got

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:47.495
all kinds of tangible assets.

00:13:49.940 --> 00:13:56.800
You would want to ask whether
this company, at the stock

00:13:56.800 --> 00:14:02.190
price it is today, is trading
for more than it would

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:04.900
take to recreate
it from scratch.

00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:09.430
And you're not going to be able
to recreate the company exactly

00:14:09.430 --> 00:14:11.530
the same from
scratch, but the idea

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:17.900
is how much capital would it
take to recreate the earnings

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:21.340
flow and the basic
business of a company.

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:23.900
So if it's selling for a lot
more in the stock market,

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:26.560
you're not going
to buy that stock.

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:29.160
Because what that's
saying is there's

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:32.740
an incentive for a
competitor to come in,

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:35.830
because they can recreate
that same company for less

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:39.110
money than the
stock price implies.

00:14:39.110 --> 00:14:44.500
So if the company in the stock
market is worth $2 billion,

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:48.550
and you could recreate that
business for $1 billion,

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:51.960
there's an incentive for
someone with a lot of money

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:55.040
to come in, create that
company for $1 billion,

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:59.360
take it public immediately, and
then basically sell the stock

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:00.700
for $2 billion in the market.

00:15:01.900 --> 00:15:06.450
So that's where we're going to
basically eliminate the company

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:10.900
from consideration if it's
trading above its replacement

00:15:10.900 --> 00:15:11.730
cost.

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:17.830
Now if it's below, then we
go to the other extreme,

00:15:17.830 --> 00:15:20.020
which is liquidation value.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:21.760
And what is liquidation value?

00:15:21.760 --> 00:15:26.300
It basically means what is
this company worth dead today?

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:29.570
So if you were to shut
down the business,

00:15:29.570 --> 00:15:32.800
or sell it, and
liquidate all the assets,

00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:35.500
how much money would
you have left over?

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.230
And if a company is
selling below that,

00:15:38.230 --> 00:15:40.560
that's usually a low
number, but sometimes

00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:42.529
companies actually
do sell below that.

00:15:42.529 --> 00:15:43.570
I'll give you an example.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:51.670
When the shipping industry--
these big ocean tankers that

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:55.040
transport crude oil around
the world, and so forth.

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:57.380
When that industry
is doing badly,

00:15:57.380 --> 00:16:02.430
it's doing generally so
badly that no one wants

00:16:02.430 --> 00:16:07.530
to own these stocks, and
they will sell, on occasion,

00:16:07.530 --> 00:16:11.880
for less than the scrap
value of the metal used

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:13.500
to build the ships.

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:21.160
So you could buy those stocks
for less than the scrap value.

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:25.070
And then, generally, management
of these companies, the CEO,

00:16:25.070 --> 00:16:29.070
they'll say, oh, the turnaround
will come next quarter.

00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:30.690
OK, maybe in a year.

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:32.700
But after two or
three years, they'll

00:16:32.700 --> 00:16:36.360
start selling the ships
for scrap themselves.

00:16:36.360 --> 00:16:38.750
And if they do
that, and the stock

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:40.430
is trading for less
than scrap, you're

00:16:40.430 --> 00:16:43.460
actually going to make money,
even though the business looks

00:16:43.460 --> 00:16:44.570
like it's going under.

00:16:46.060 --> 00:16:48.170
So that's another easy one.

00:16:48.170 --> 00:16:50.240
You would take control
of the company,

00:16:50.240 --> 00:16:53.600
you would liquidate
it, you'd make money.

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:59.660
Now beyond that-- those are kind
of the two bounds, the upper

00:16:59.660 --> 00:17:02.620
and lower bounds--
you get into where

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:05.274
you're looking at actual
earning power of the company.

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:09.230
And this is where
most companies end up,

00:17:09.230 --> 00:17:13.790
unless we're in a 2008 financial
crisis-type scenario, where

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:16.220
there were a lot of
companies selling

00:17:16.220 --> 00:17:19.319
for less than their
liquidation value.

00:17:19.319 --> 00:17:24.400
And what you would
look at here is

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:27.710
how much is this company
actually earning,

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:30.410
and how much do I have to
pay in the stock market

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:32.790
to acquire the whole business?

00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:35.450
And there's no right
or wrong answer.

00:17:35.450 --> 00:17:40.370
So you would basically decide,
well, what kind of return

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:42.410
is good enough for my savings?

00:17:42.410 --> 00:17:46.260
If a company's earning
$1 billion a year,

00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:51.190
and it takes $10 billion to
buy it in the stock market,

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:53.917
that's a 10% a year return.

00:17:53.917 --> 00:17:55.500
And then maybe you
want to know, well,

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:57.530
are those earnings
growing over time?

00:17:57.530 --> 00:18:02.190
So my 10% in year one
will be 11%, and then 12%,

00:18:02.190 --> 00:18:02.960
and so forth.

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:04.870
Or are the earnings declining?

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:10.920
In which case you'll want
a higher initial percentage

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:12.120
yield.

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:14.990
So maybe even if the earnings
are going to decline,

00:18:14.990 --> 00:18:20.380
well, if you can acquire it
for two times current earnings,

00:18:20.380 --> 00:18:25.160
that means you're making
50% return just based on--

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:29.860
and we have the mindset of a
capital allocator and owner

00:18:29.860 --> 00:18:34.085
here, no longer just
pieces of paper and stocks.

00:18:34.085 --> 00:18:37.240
If you can buy the whole
company and in one year

00:18:37.240 --> 00:18:40.716
get half your money
back in earnings,

00:18:40.716 --> 00:18:42.090
you're probably
going to be fine,

00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:44.900
even if those earnings are
going down slowly over time.

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:46.880
Because within two
to three years,

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:48.930
you've got all your money
back, and then whatever

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:51.420
comes after that is just gravy.

00:18:53.540 --> 00:18:57.560
So here you're making a decision
whether the earnings yield--

00:18:57.560 --> 00:18:59.730
that's the earnings
before interest and tax--

00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:01.680
and these are some
technical terms here,

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:05.270
but I'm telling you
the essence of what's

00:19:05.270 --> 00:19:10.100
on here-- if those earnings
divided by what the company's

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:14.396
worth in the market exceed
whatever return you require--

00:19:14.396 --> 00:19:16.770
because you're going to look
at your alternatives, right?

00:19:17.980 --> 00:19:21.820
You can put money in a
CD, you can buy a bond,

00:19:21.820 --> 00:19:23.960
you can do all kinds of things.

00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:27.200
If that exceeds your
return, you move on here.

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:30.409
If it doesn't, you eliminate
this particular company

00:19:30.409 --> 00:19:31.200
from consideration.

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:34.580
And now what we're
talking about here

00:19:34.580 --> 00:19:39.440
is we're looking at the
business itself now.

00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:40.890
Forget the stock market.

00:19:40.890 --> 00:19:43.765
We just want to know how
good is this company.

00:19:45.410 --> 00:19:49.640
And because we're
dealing with money here,

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:53.390
we want the company to make
as much money as possible

00:19:53.390 --> 00:19:58.630
in earnings or cash flow
relative to the capital it

00:19:58.630 --> 00:20:02.480
takes to build that company.

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:08.540
So if I need to have a factory
that costs me $1 billion,

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:13.860
and that factory is then going
to throw off $10 million a year

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:17.560
in profit, that's
probably not good enough.

00:20:17.560 --> 00:20:23.390
Because that's a 1% return,
and a factory is no CD,

00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:26.530
it's not a safe
investment, and so forth.

00:20:26.530 --> 00:20:28.716
So you really want to know
how good is the business.

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:35.170
Google, for example, doesn't
take a whole lot of capital,

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:39.130
and it throws off a
lot of free cash flow

00:20:39.130 --> 00:20:41.240
relative to that
capital, so that's

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:43.172
why it's a great business.

00:20:43.172 --> 00:20:44.630
And that's the kind
of business you

00:20:44.630 --> 00:20:48.750
want to be in, because
when you buy a stock,

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:52.260
they're not actually going to
pay you out all their earnings

00:20:52.260 --> 00:20:53.320
every year.

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:56.980
Now if they just took their
earnings and paid them out,

00:20:56.980 --> 00:21:00.255
you may not even care
how good of a business

00:21:00.255 --> 00:21:02.130
it is, because you're
getting those earnings.

00:21:02.130 --> 00:21:04.520
Like I mentioned, if
you're buying a company

00:21:04.520 --> 00:21:09.350
with a 50% earnings yield,
and they paid everything out,

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:13.510
you got your money back in
a little over two years,

00:21:13.510 --> 00:21:14.270
and that's fine.

00:21:14.270 --> 00:21:18.780
But because most companies will
actually retain those earnings

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:23.410
in the business, you
care very much about when

00:21:23.410 --> 00:21:25.860
they retain those earnings.

00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:28.480
They're going to invest
them in their business,

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:32.050
and what is the return
on that capital?

00:21:34.480 --> 00:21:39.200
Some companies pay
dividends, so that's

00:21:39.200 --> 00:21:41.990
a portion of the
earnings, usually.

00:21:41.990 --> 00:21:44.020
They won't pay out
their whole earnings,

00:21:44.020 --> 00:21:46.435
they'll pay out half,
if you're lucky.

00:21:47.610 --> 00:21:50.240
So there you may care
a little bit less,

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:52.090
because you are
getting some cash back.

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:55.310
But where you're not
basically getting cash back,

00:21:55.310 --> 00:21:57.970
you want to know
what kind of return

00:21:57.970 --> 00:22:00.280
is this company getting
on the cash that

00:22:00.280 --> 00:22:01.870
stays in the business.

00:22:01.870 --> 00:22:05.530
And if it's a great business,
like Google, the problem

00:22:05.530 --> 00:22:12.230
actually becomes that it's very
hard to reinvest that cash,

00:22:12.230 --> 00:22:15.085
because the business doesn't
require a lot of capital.

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:23.175
So take one year's worth of
free cash flow for Google.

00:22:24.220 --> 00:22:27.040
If it could be reinvested
in the business

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:29.630
at the kinds of returns
that Google is currently

00:22:29.630 --> 00:22:32.540
getting on its capital,
that would be phenomenal.

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:36.230
But because it's not a
capital-intensive business,

00:22:36.230 --> 00:22:39.930
that free cash flow just kind of
builds up on the balance sheet,

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:42.570
and over time
there's tens and tens

00:22:42.570 --> 00:22:45.420
of billions of cash
on the balance sheet.

00:22:47.560 --> 00:22:53.260
So if we like the
quality of the business,

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:58.310
as measured by the earnings
divided by the capital employed

00:22:58.310 --> 00:23:02.000
in the business, then it's a
good potential opportunity.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.065
And it still doesn't mean
that it's a great investment.

00:23:06.070 --> 00:23:12.430
But you've kind of eliminated
all the obvious candidates

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:14.640
that are just not good enough.

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:23.290
And then once you're here, it
becomes really more of an art,

00:23:23.290 --> 00:23:25.895
which company you are going
to invest in versus another.

00:23:27.550 --> 00:23:30.415
And we're going to get
into some of that here.

00:23:31.700 --> 00:23:39.995
So here are some value-oriented
investment approaches.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:47.740
You might have heard of value
investing and growth investing.

00:23:47.740 --> 00:23:51.260
So growth investing,
usually it's

00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:53.960
kind of the other mindset,
or just the mindset

00:23:53.960 --> 00:23:57.000
of which company is
going to grow the fastest

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:58.530
and that's where
I want to invest.

00:23:58.530 --> 00:24:00.120
But you're not really
thinking, well,

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:01.660
what if everyone
else thinks it's

00:24:01.660 --> 00:24:04.840
going to grow the fastest
as you're super expensive.

00:24:04.840 --> 00:24:06.330
You may not make any money.

00:24:06.330 --> 00:24:08.520
If they have any kind
of disappointment,

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:11.930
like they missed a
quarter by a penny,

00:24:11.930 --> 00:24:14.340
the stock can be
down 20% in a day,

00:24:14.340 --> 00:24:16.730
because there was
just no value there.

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:21.650
So we want to buy things that
are more valuable than what

00:24:21.650 --> 00:24:24.320
we're paying for them
in the stock market.

00:24:24.320 --> 00:24:29.420
And some of the well-known
approaches in this area--

00:24:29.420 --> 00:24:33.200
there's the Benjamin
Graham style, deep value.

00:24:33.200 --> 00:24:36.670
And I start with that because
Benjamin Graham wrote the book

00:24:36.670 --> 00:24:38.440
on value investing.

00:24:38.440 --> 00:24:42.900
It's called "The
Intelligent Investor."

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:46.780
And the style is today
called deep value

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:49.710
because you focus
mostly on the assets--

00:24:49.710 --> 00:24:52.040
like I mentioned
a shipping company

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:55.130
with their ships
and the scrap value.

00:24:55.130 --> 00:24:56.910
That would be deep
value, if you can

00:24:56.910 --> 00:24:59.755
buy something for
less than the assets.

00:25:01.070 --> 00:25:01.600
Question?

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:02.532
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
have a question.

00:25:02.532 --> 00:25:03.823
How would you find [INAUDIBLE]?

00:25:12.689 --> 00:25:13.730
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Correct.

00:25:13.730 --> 00:25:17.610
So really what you're
going to look at

00:25:17.610 --> 00:25:20.740
is the financial
statements of a company,

00:25:20.740 --> 00:25:23.860
and that's where we get kind of
into the language of investing,

00:25:23.860 --> 00:25:25.400
which is really accounting.

00:25:25.400 --> 00:25:31.340
So every company will have
a line item on their balance

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:35.250
sheet called property,
plant, and equipment.

00:25:35.250 --> 00:25:36.940
And for a shipping
company, that's

00:25:36.940 --> 00:25:39.000
where their ships might be.

00:25:40.360 --> 00:25:43.620
For a hotel company
that owns hotels,

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:45.540
that's where their
hotels would be.

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:49.220
And then they may have a
footnote in their annual report

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:51.420
that actually lists
out the ships.

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:54.050
It won't necessarily
tell you the market value

00:25:54.050 --> 00:25:55.510
of those ships,
but it might tell

00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:58.650
you what they're
carried on on the books,

00:25:58.650 --> 00:26:02.500
and how much they've depreciated
so far, and some detail.

00:26:02.500 --> 00:26:05.830
But you're going to have
to dig a little bit deeper

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:10.610
if you want to know the market
value of specific ships,

00:26:10.610 --> 00:26:14.017
or specific real estate,
or something like that.

00:26:14.017 --> 00:26:15.850
AUDIENCE: John, can you
repeat the question?

00:26:18.464 --> 00:26:19.380
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Yeah.

00:26:19.380 --> 00:26:22.400
The question was,
how do you actually

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:26.750
find companies that
maybe have those ships

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:28.300
and trade for less than that.

00:26:28.300 --> 00:26:34.100
So you could use a
quantitative stock screener

00:26:34.100 --> 00:26:37.760
that looks for companies
that have market

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:41.980
value less than
tangible book value.

00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:46.260
And tangible book
value is once you

00:26:46.260 --> 00:26:50.120
satisfy all the liabilities--
like the debt-- what's

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:55.010
left over for the shareholders,
using this accounting

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:57.730
language-- which
is standardized,

00:26:57.730 --> 00:27:03.380
but it's not really correct
in an economic sense.

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:04.960
But you can use
it for screening,

00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:08.610
and then you have to do your
own research to decide, well,

00:27:08.610 --> 00:27:13.010
the book value may be high,
but that's not actually

00:27:13.010 --> 00:27:17.780
if I wanted to sell the ships,
so you take it down and do

00:27:17.780 --> 00:27:18.735
that kind of analysis.

00:27:21.030 --> 00:27:25.030
Now Joel Greenblatt is a
very successful investor.

00:27:25.030 --> 00:27:29.300
He's written a book called
"The Little Book That Beats

00:27:29.300 --> 00:27:33.820
the Market," where he talks
about this magic formula.

00:27:33.820 --> 00:27:39.640
It's essentially a way to screen
for companies that, according

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:42.510
to my previous
schematic, would be

00:27:42.510 --> 00:27:45.230
in that green
portion at the end,

00:27:45.230 --> 00:27:47.700
and then you can invest in them.

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:49.320
And it looks at two factors.

00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:53.010
One is the high earnings
yield, how cheap is a business.

00:27:53.010 --> 00:27:55.460
And the other is the
high return on capital,

00:27:55.460 --> 00:27:57.140
how good is a business.

00:27:57.140 --> 00:28:00.570
And historically, just
a mechanical screen

00:28:00.570 --> 00:28:04.190
of those companies that rank
highly on those two metrics

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:09.100
has outperformed the S&amp;P
500 by several percentage

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:10.540
points a year.

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:13.120
And over time, due to
compounding, that just

00:28:13.120 --> 00:28:13.970
is a huge number.

00:28:16.340 --> 00:28:20.200
Then we have what I call
here Carl Icahn-style,

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:23.240
sum-of-the-parts investing.

00:28:23.240 --> 00:28:25.050
You may have heard
of Carl Icahn,

00:28:25.050 --> 00:28:31.260
or these activist investors,
who will buy a big chunk

00:28:31.260 --> 00:28:37.670
of a company-- maybe 10%-- and
then try to tell the company

00:28:37.670 --> 00:28:42.420
what to do so that the stock
would be worth more, or go up.

00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:45.750
And usually what
they look for is

00:28:45.750 --> 00:28:51.240
where you have a company that
has different parts to it,

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:54.860
and if you add up the
value of all the parts,

00:28:54.860 --> 00:28:57.350
it's materially above
what the whole company

00:28:57.350 --> 00:28:59.715
is trading for in the
stock markets today.

00:29:01.110 --> 00:29:05.240
And that can happen quite often,
because maybe a company has

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:09.180
a core business, and that's
what investors are focused on,

00:29:09.180 --> 00:29:11.470
and they value the
company based on that.

00:29:11.470 --> 00:29:13.490
But then there may
be something else

00:29:13.490 --> 00:29:17.380
that they own that's totally
unrelated-- like some big piece

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:19.830
of real estate, or
some other business.

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:24.360
And then there are
some other approaches,

00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:26.800
what I call jockey
stocks, which is really

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:29.860
companies that are
run by a great jockey.

00:29:29.860 --> 00:29:34.310
It's again the horse
racing kind of analogy,

00:29:34.310 --> 00:29:38.140
where you have a CEO who is
not just great at running

00:29:38.140 --> 00:29:42.194
the business, but also great
at what he does with the cash

00:29:42.194 --> 00:29:43.360
that the business generates.

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:48.330
Because once the cash is there,
there are a lot of options.

00:29:48.330 --> 00:29:51.550
And you can destroy a lot
of value is a company,

00:29:51.550 --> 00:29:55.040
or create a lot of value, based
on what you do with the cash.

00:29:55.040 --> 00:29:57.750
So it's especially
relevant for companies

00:29:57.750 --> 00:30:00.590
that have a ton of cash
on their balance sheet.

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:03.560
You might make an
acquisition, you

00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:05.530
could overpay for
another business,

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:08.060
just because you
fear you're going

00:30:08.060 --> 00:30:10.510
to miss out on the next trend.

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:12.280
And you take that
hard earned cash

00:30:12.280 --> 00:30:15.270
and you could
basically waste it.

00:30:15.270 --> 00:30:20.130
Or if your stock
price gets low--

00:30:20.130 --> 00:30:23.480
let's say there's a financial
crisis and the stock gets hit,

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:25.160
and it's trading
way below what it's

00:30:25.160 --> 00:30:29.740
worth-- the company could
actually take the cash hoard

00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:33.560
and buy its own stock
in the stock market,

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:35.390
and create huge value.

00:30:35.390 --> 00:30:37.160
Because if it's
just sitting there,

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:40.830
the cash is maybe
earning 0%, 1%, 2%.

00:30:40.830 --> 00:30:46.420
But if you're buying your own
stock at yields of 10% or more,

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:48.070
you're going to
create huge value.

00:30:49.430 --> 00:30:54.810
So I want to maybe get
into a couple of these

00:30:54.810 --> 00:30:58.240
quickly, and then
take questions.

00:30:58.240 --> 00:31:04.420
But these are basically these
buckets we just talked about.

00:31:04.420 --> 00:31:07.430
And I'm not a huge
fan of buckets,

00:31:07.430 --> 00:31:09.750
because once you
get into that, then

00:31:09.750 --> 00:31:12.880
it becomes a little
bit more mechanical.

00:31:12.880 --> 00:31:15.050
You find a company, and
all of a sudden you're

00:31:15.050 --> 00:31:17.410
thinking, well, what
bucket does it fit in?

00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:19.310
And how do I have to analyze it?

00:31:19.310 --> 00:31:21.940
When really it should
just be common sense.

00:31:21.940 --> 00:31:24.820
You should just take
a company, imagine

00:31:24.820 --> 00:31:28.180
you own the whole thing,
and think like an owner,

00:31:28.180 --> 00:31:30.100
basically, from scratch.

00:31:30.100 --> 00:31:32.700
But nonetheless, let's
just touch on some

00:31:32.700 --> 00:31:37.090
of the key features of some
of these types of companies.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:39.160
So these deeper
value companies where

00:31:39.160 --> 00:31:45.400
you're buying maybe some
factory-type business

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:51.480
for less than it would
cost to create the factory,

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:54.240
these are generally
hated stocks.

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:59.530
And if you look at
it historically,

00:31:59.530 --> 00:32:03.220
people have overreacted on
the negative, generally.

00:32:03.220 --> 00:32:11.640
So this guy, Jeroen Bos,
he's a successful investor

00:32:11.640 --> 00:32:13.710
who just invests in
these hated companies.

00:32:15.040 --> 00:32:18.010
So he says it's kind
of contradictory

00:32:18.010 --> 00:32:21.380
that you buy what no one else
wants, and then you outperform.

00:32:23.220 --> 00:32:25.370
And it just takes
a certain mindset

00:32:25.370 --> 00:32:29.300
to be comfortable doing that,
because everyone around you

00:32:29.300 --> 00:32:32.820
will say, oh, you
are not very smart.

00:32:35.500 --> 00:32:39.540
And imagine if an
investment doesn't work out,

00:32:39.540 --> 00:32:41.540
you're really going to
not feel very smart.

00:32:41.540 --> 00:32:44.550
Because everyone was telling
you all along, and then that's

00:32:44.550 --> 00:32:45.840
what happened.

00:32:45.840 --> 00:32:50.330
So even when people
start off like this,

00:32:50.330 --> 00:32:52.430
they can't sustain
it for very long.

00:32:52.430 --> 00:32:55.840
Because after a while they
just think, you know what?

00:32:55.840 --> 00:32:59.070
It's too hard, and
I can handle it,

00:32:59.070 --> 00:33:01.980
so I'm going to move on to
one of the more comfortable

00:33:01.980 --> 00:33:04.330
approaches, where you
buy great companies,

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:08.680
and you pay more for them,
but at least no one's

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:12.480
going to tell you that you're
making an obvious mistake.

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:16.030
But then, they
actually do outperform.

00:33:17.810 --> 00:33:21.450
And it's kind of the reward for
the discomfort, if you will.

00:33:22.930 --> 00:33:27.490
These are some takeaways that
I basically have in the book

00:33:27.490 --> 00:33:30.440
related to this
chapter on deep value.

00:33:31.610 --> 00:33:34.530
And I'll just kind of
highlight the first one,

00:33:34.530 --> 00:33:37.420
which is we start with
the price of the stock.

00:33:37.420 --> 00:33:40.590
So when you talk to
Jeroen Bos, or one

00:33:40.590 --> 00:33:46.050
of the other investors who focus
on these kinds of companies,

00:33:46.050 --> 00:33:49.540
the first thing they'll talk
about is wow, this is so cheap.

00:33:49.540 --> 00:33:52.120
And then after two minutes,
you ask them, well,

00:33:52.120 --> 00:33:54.260
what does the company do?

00:33:54.260 --> 00:33:58.070
So they really just care
that it's really cheap,

00:33:58.070 --> 00:34:02.780
kind of the bargain
basement pricing.

00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:08.060
And here's an
example of a company

00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:13.460
that somebody presented at
one of the online conferences

00:34:13.460 --> 00:34:14.766
we've hosted for investors.

00:34:16.090 --> 00:34:24.199
And the basic thesis here-- this
is a tire manufacturer in Korea

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:26.820
that has a few different
types of stock,

00:34:26.820 --> 00:34:30.969
so it gets a little complicated.

00:34:30.969 --> 00:34:35.070
But basically, you can
invest in this company

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:40.770
in a few different ways, and the
basic way-- the common stock--

00:34:40.770 --> 00:34:42.199
is cheap.

00:34:42.199 --> 00:34:45.790
But then there's another way,
through the preferred stock,

00:34:45.790 --> 00:34:51.960
where you're getting this
exact same thing 50% cheaper

00:34:51.960 --> 00:34:55.230
than other people are
paying for the other thing.

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:57.440
And the other thing
they're paying more,

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:02.750
basically because it's a little
bit more well-known, or has

00:35:02.750 --> 00:35:04.810
more trading going on.

00:35:04.810 --> 00:35:10.390
So sometimes people will
care about liquidity a lot

00:35:10.390 --> 00:35:11.170
in a stock.

00:35:11.170 --> 00:35:15.790
Oh, can I buy $10 million
of this in one day,

00:35:15.790 --> 00:35:18.010
or does it trade very little?

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:20.170
When actually,
how much it trades

00:35:20.170 --> 00:35:23.520
has nothing to do with
how much it's worth.

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:26.450
I mean, if you own a
house it trades zero,

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:29.280
and it's still worth
whatever it's worth.

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:33.720
So the preferreds trade at a
big discount to the common,

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:38.030
and that's just an example
of a deep value investment.

00:35:38.030 --> 00:35:40.300
AUDIENCE: John, can you go
back to the previous slide?

00:35:40.854 --> 00:35:41.770
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Sure.

00:35:41.770 --> 00:35:42.978
AUDIENCE: One quick question.

00:35:42.978 --> 00:35:45.790
On point number two, you
said no voting rights,

00:35:45.790 --> 00:35:48.506
but confer some
economic benefits.

00:35:48.506 --> 00:35:49.630
Can you explain that point?

00:35:51.424 --> 00:35:52.340
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Sure.

00:35:52.340 --> 00:35:55.670
So depending on
the class of stock,

00:35:55.670 --> 00:35:58.300
the voting rights may be
a little bit different,

00:35:58.300 --> 00:36:03.100
which just means do
you get to decide

00:36:03.100 --> 00:36:06.370
who is on the board of
directors, and so forth.

00:36:06.370 --> 00:36:09.880
And companies do that
for different reasons.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:14.410
Actually, Google has,
I think, two or now

00:36:14.410 --> 00:36:16.380
three classes of stock.

00:36:16.380 --> 00:36:21.720
And the purpose there
is really to make sure

00:36:21.720 --> 00:36:25.620
that the founders
retain operating control

00:36:25.620 --> 00:36:28.890
of the company, and can
make the decisions that

00:36:28.890 --> 00:36:31.230
are needed for the future.

00:36:31.230 --> 00:36:36.020
Because you wouldn't necessarily
want an outside investor

00:36:36.020 --> 00:36:39.290
to come in and buy
up enough shares

00:36:39.290 --> 00:36:43.760
to get voting control of a
company, and then do something

00:36:43.760 --> 00:36:45.810
that may move the stock
in the short term,

00:36:45.810 --> 00:36:48.200
but may destroy value
in the long term.

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:54.660
So one way to do that is to
sell non-voting stock, or shares

00:36:54.660 --> 00:36:57.420
that have fewer votes,
to public investors,

00:36:57.420 --> 00:37:01.320
so that they can never gain
a majority of the vote.

00:37:01.320 --> 00:37:03.450
And these preferreds
have no voting rights,

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:07.350
but this is a Korean
tire manufacturer.

00:37:07.350 --> 00:37:10.880
Even if you're buying the
stock that has voting rights,

00:37:10.880 --> 00:37:13.350
there's no practical
difference, because you're not

00:37:13.350 --> 00:37:17.240
going to be able to influence
it in any way, either way.

00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:22.520
So the voting rights
are not worth very much,

00:37:22.520 --> 00:37:24.850
but you're getting the
same economic benefits.

00:37:24.850 --> 00:37:28.700
So if the common
shareholders get $1 dividend,

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:32.460
you'll get $1 dividend, but
you're paying half the price

00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:33.625
for the preferred stock.

00:37:38.270 --> 00:37:43.750
Sum-of-the-parts, there are
many examples of this kind

00:37:43.750 --> 00:37:44.250
of-- Yeah?

00:37:44.250 --> 00:37:45.166
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:55.372 --> 00:37:57.330
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:37:57.330 --> 00:38:00.430
And actually they can stay
cheaper for a very long time.

00:38:01.970 --> 00:38:05.950
Sometimes a company may, if
the company's smart, or cares

00:38:05.950 --> 00:38:08.810
about the value,
they may actually

00:38:08.810 --> 00:38:12.007
buy that preferred
stock themselves,

00:38:12.007 --> 00:38:14.090
because it's so much cheaper
than the other stock.

00:38:14.090 --> 00:38:17.410
They could sell the other
stock in the market,

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:19.810
and then use the money to
buy back the preferred.

00:38:19.810 --> 00:38:24.555
But absent that, you're right,
the disparity could continue.

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:32.040
But would you rather buy
the one at 50% discount,

00:38:32.040 --> 00:38:35.880
and maybe it stays at
a discount, maybe not.

00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:40.790
The discount could get wider,
but I think probabilistically,

00:38:40.790 --> 00:38:43.360
you're much better off
buying it at a discount.

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:47.610
And it turns out
that over time, they

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:51.160
do tend to work out, because
some large shareholders would

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:54.250
move in, and they'll just
kind of start putting pressure

00:38:54.250 --> 00:38:56.790
on the management to
eliminate this disparity.

00:38:59.276 --> 00:39:00.192
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:09.624 --> 00:39:10.790
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Absolutely.

00:39:10.790 --> 00:39:13.860
And sometimes preferred
stock-- or often-- it's

00:39:13.860 --> 00:39:17.560
a better security because it
ranks ahead of the common.

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:20.555
In case of bankruptcy, it
may have certain preferences.

00:39:21.730 --> 00:39:26.360
But because a lot of investors
are so focused on liquidity,

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:29.390
meaning being able to--
if I decide tomorrow,

00:39:29.390 --> 00:39:30.930
I want to dump
this stock-- being

00:39:30.930 --> 00:39:33.750
able to dump it in one
day, versus taking a week

00:39:33.750 --> 00:39:35.560
to sell it slowly.

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:39.110
They put such a premium on
that, that the preferred-- even

00:39:39.110 --> 00:39:42.600
though it's a better security--
may trade at a big discount

00:39:42.600 --> 00:39:43.820
to the common.

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:46.710
And to a long-term investor
that makes no sense.

00:39:46.710 --> 00:39:50.575
So you can buy that preferred
slowly, you can sell it slowly,

00:39:50.575 --> 00:39:52.775
and over time you're
going to make more money.

00:39:58.110 --> 00:40:00.840
There are some examples
of sum-of-the-parts are

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:03.870
so obvious, they're at
very large companies.

00:40:03.870 --> 00:40:07.650
So there was a couple
years ago, Vodafone,

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:13.520
which is a big mobile phone
carrier based in the UK,

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:17.640
owned a large stake in
Verizon Wireless in the US.

00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:22.790
And Verizon Wireless
publicly traded so just

00:40:22.790 --> 00:40:26.290
that the value of that
stake was so great

00:40:26.290 --> 00:40:29.795
that the rest of Vodafone was
being valued extremely cheaply.

00:40:30.910 --> 00:40:36.310
But investors didn't see
care to see it for a while,

00:40:36.310 --> 00:40:38.360
and it's hard to
predict these things,

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:40.990
but usually it
works out, and then

00:40:40.990 --> 00:40:44.390
after a couple of years, all
of a sudden it worked out,

00:40:44.390 --> 00:40:46.680
and you actually
make a great return.

00:40:48.740 --> 00:40:50.760
Even though you
didn't quite know when

00:40:50.760 --> 00:40:53.815
that disparity would be removed.

00:40:56.160 --> 00:41:01.330
And so, sometimes it makes sense
to analyze the different parts

00:41:01.330 --> 00:41:08.000
of a company separately, and
then sum up all those values

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:10.920
to decide what is this
business really worth.

00:41:12.970 --> 00:41:16.420
And I'll just make a kind
of a side comment here.

00:41:16.420 --> 00:41:20.950
So whether you're adding
up different parts,

00:41:20.950 --> 00:41:26.701
or just using an earnings
yield, or what have you,

00:41:26.701 --> 00:41:33.130
you really need to
know-- or basically

00:41:33.130 --> 00:41:35.840
have an estimate
that you believe in--

00:41:35.840 --> 00:41:39.410
that a company's worth
before you can even

00:41:39.410 --> 00:41:41.310
think about investing in it.

00:41:41.310 --> 00:41:48.890
Because if you don't know what
you think a business is worth,

00:41:48.890 --> 00:41:51.695
then there's no basis to
make an investment decision.

00:41:53.370 --> 00:41:56.090
And I think that's
often forgotten.

00:41:56.090 --> 00:41:59.550
Sometimes you'll just
hear someone say, oh, you

00:41:59.550 --> 00:42:01.350
should buy Apple
stock, because they're

00:42:01.350 --> 00:42:03.520
going to come up
with a new iPhone.

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:06.490
And there's no reference in
that sentence to how much

00:42:06.490 --> 00:42:08.360
you have to pay for Apple.

00:42:08.360 --> 00:42:12.580
Could be $100 billion,
could be $200 billion.

00:42:12.580 --> 00:42:17.350
So maybe the fact that they're
coming out with a new product

00:42:17.350 --> 00:42:20.970
is already reflected
in that market value--

00:42:20.970 --> 00:42:23.550
and actually if the
new product is not

00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:27.220
quite as great, the
stock goes down.

00:42:27.220 --> 00:42:30.290
So you really need
to think about what

00:42:30.290 --> 00:42:32.790
is this business worth
in the stock market,

00:42:32.790 --> 00:42:34.900
and what do I value it at.

00:42:34.900 --> 00:42:37.320
If I had the money,
how much would

00:42:37.320 --> 00:42:41.030
I want to pay for that
company to own all of it,

00:42:41.030 --> 00:42:44.020
and just make money off the
cash flow of the company.

00:42:48.670 --> 00:42:51.340
And here's just kind
of a classic example

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:52.540
of sum-of-the-parts.

00:42:52.540 --> 00:42:58.540
Where you have this little
company in India where

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:02.790
they got $50 million
cash, they have a big plot

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:07.980
of land near Mumbai airport,
and both of those things

00:43:07.980 --> 00:43:11.400
together are already
worth more than

00:43:11.400 --> 00:43:14.970
what the whole company's
trading for in the stock market.

00:43:14.970 --> 00:43:17.810
So you're actually getting
the business, whatever

00:43:17.810 --> 00:43:22.790
it is that they do-- which
is an exhibition and IT parks

00:43:22.790 --> 00:43:25.450
business-- you're
getting that for free.

00:43:25.450 --> 00:43:29.230
And that may or may
not be a good deal,

00:43:29.230 --> 00:43:32.550
but at least you found something
that looks kind of interesting.

00:43:32.550 --> 00:43:36.470
Because if they sold that
land, or gave back that cash

00:43:36.470 --> 00:43:41.070
to the shareholders, you get
your investment right back,

00:43:41.070 --> 00:43:42.645
and you own this business.

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:47.560
So that's an interesting
type of set up,

00:43:47.560 --> 00:43:50.860
and that would fit into
sum-of-the-parts category.

00:43:54.190 --> 00:43:56.430
I'll just touch very
briefly on magic formula,

00:43:56.430 --> 00:43:58.520
and then we'll open
it up for questions.

00:44:01.010 --> 00:44:05.590
Here we were talking about
the two factors screening,

00:44:05.590 --> 00:44:07.925
looking for cheap stocks
and good companies.

00:44:10.280 --> 00:44:14.860
Alon Bochman is an investor
who focuses on that.

00:44:14.860 --> 00:44:22.150
And an interesting finding
is that if you gave people

00:44:22.150 --> 00:44:26.010
the lists of those companies
that rank highly on those two

00:44:26.010 --> 00:44:31.040
factors and told them, well, now
that you have these companies,

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:34.060
choose the best
ones-- or now, use

00:44:34.060 --> 00:44:36.210
your own judgments
to choose which ones

00:44:36.210 --> 00:44:37.290
you want to invest in.

00:44:37.290 --> 00:44:41.330
What they found is actually,
when people choose their own,

00:44:41.330 --> 00:44:46.250
they do worse than the
mechanical screen does.

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:50.260
And it's interesting but
it's also kind of intuitive,

00:44:50.260 --> 00:44:54.700
because there we go back
to the discomfort of owning

00:44:54.700 --> 00:44:56.200
hated businesses.

00:44:56.200 --> 00:44:58.990
If they're that's
cheap, they're usually

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:02.070
companies that have fallen
a little bit on hard times.

00:45:02.070 --> 00:45:03.650
And when you're
looking at that list,

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:06.460
you're going to want to
eliminate any company that

00:45:06.460 --> 00:45:08.410
doesn't feel quite right.

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:10.630
But they're priced so
cheaply that they'll actually

00:45:10.630 --> 00:45:11.130
outperform.

00:45:15.550 --> 00:45:19.010
And so I'll end it there.

00:45:19.010 --> 00:45:22.880
There's one more approach
discussed in the slide deck

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:27.180
that we're going
to skip over now,

00:45:27.180 --> 00:45:31.510
but it deals with the quality
of the management team.

00:45:31.510 --> 00:45:35.230
And the point that I just
want to kind of leave

00:45:35.230 --> 00:45:38.290
with all of you is,
there's no secret,

00:45:38.290 --> 00:45:40.880
there's no magic to this.

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:45.210
And the only way to do
well in the long term

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:50.010
is to find businesses
where you feel like you're

00:45:50.010 --> 00:45:54.750
comfortable with it,
and it's cheap enough

00:45:54.750 --> 00:45:58.060
in the stock market that
you feel like the return

00:45:58.060 --> 00:46:01.080
you're getting from
the business itself

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:02.440
is going to make it worthwhile.

00:46:04.290 --> 00:46:09.320
Ben Graham, who wrote that
original book on investing,

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:12.650
he said in the short
term, the stock market

00:46:12.650 --> 00:46:15.230
is a voting machine.

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:18.290
And in the long term,
it's a weighing machine.

00:46:18.290 --> 00:46:21.350
So in the short term,
there's the beauty contest,

00:46:21.350 --> 00:46:23.560
there's all this
noise out there.

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:25.570
And when you turn
on CNBC, they're

00:46:25.570 --> 00:46:29.460
always talking about this
quarter, or today even,

00:46:29.460 --> 00:46:32.640
or tomorrow, what's
going to happen.

00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:34.340
That's just noise.

00:46:34.340 --> 00:46:35.780
There's no signal there.

00:46:38.310 --> 00:46:41.260
But in the long term,
there's that mystery.

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:44.270
So how do you go from a voting
machine to a weighing machine?

00:46:44.270 --> 00:46:49.170
But I guess over time, the
earnings of the business

00:46:49.170 --> 00:46:52.350
come in, and people
settle down, whatever

00:46:52.350 --> 00:46:56.670
emotion they had on
that day dissipates.

00:46:56.670 --> 00:47:01.270
When there was the oil
spill in the Gulf of Mexico,

00:47:01.270 --> 00:47:04.080
BP's stock got
killed, because they

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:07.950
were operating that
well that had the spill.

00:47:07.950 --> 00:47:10.090
And that was the
voting machine, right?

00:47:10.090 --> 00:47:12.880
People were saying
BP is going bankrupt.

00:47:12.880 --> 00:47:15.280
And then as people
start to think, well,

00:47:15.280 --> 00:47:16.720
what are the scenarios?

00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:19.660
How much could they have to pay?

00:47:19.660 --> 00:47:22.395
And even in the
worst case scenario,

00:47:22.395 --> 00:47:27.890
if they had to pay $20 billion
to clean up this oil spill,

00:47:27.890 --> 00:47:31.130
they'd still be undervalued
because the stock has gone down

00:47:31.130 --> 00:47:31.730
so much.

00:47:31.730 --> 00:47:34.230
And over time, the
stock went back up,

00:47:34.230 --> 00:47:38.020
because people realized
what BP was actually worth.

00:47:40.230 --> 00:47:43.680
So with that, I will open
it up to any questions.

00:47:46.141 --> 00:47:46.640
Yeah?

00:47:48.750 --> 00:47:52.904
AUDIENCE: So you always have
to be ahead of the market

00:47:52.904 --> 00:47:57.336
price, which is representative
of the current prediction

00:47:57.336 --> 00:48:01.134
that other people have made
and according to [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:01.134 --> 00:48:04.062
So if you want to find some
investment opportunity that

00:48:04.062 --> 00:48:06.990
is worthwhile, you have to
make a better prediction

00:48:06.990 --> 00:48:08.454
than all those [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:08.454 --> 00:48:10.854
So you have to find
one where others

00:48:10.854 --> 00:48:13.640
have made a bad prediction.

00:48:13.640 --> 00:48:16.330
This requires
[INAUDIBLE], so is it

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:19.190
feasible for a small
scale investor who's

00:48:19.190 --> 00:48:25.480
going [INAUDIBLE] profit from
it to actually be worth the time

00:48:25.480 --> 00:48:26.362
[INAUDIBLE].

00:48:26.362 --> 00:48:28.320
JOHN MIHALJEVIC: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:48:28.320 --> 00:48:34.060
So the stock price does reflect
the opinion of the market.

00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:39.820
And just to be technical, it's
not the actual stock price,

00:48:39.820 --> 00:48:41.640
it's the market capitalization.

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:44.890
So it's stock price times
number of shares outstanding.

00:48:47.830 --> 00:48:50.740
And it'll have a
prediction built in,

00:48:50.740 --> 00:48:56.270
but you don't need to outsmart
the market on the prediction

00:48:56.270 --> 00:48:59.360
necessarily,
because you can just

00:48:59.360 --> 00:49:02.340
decide what you're
comfortable with.

00:49:02.340 --> 00:49:08.970
So if the company's earning
$1 billion in free cash flow,

00:49:08.970 --> 00:49:14.900
or net income per year, and
it's selling for $10 billion,

00:49:14.900 --> 00:49:17.230
that's a 10% yield.

00:49:17.230 --> 00:49:20.600
And you can say, well,
I'm comfortable with that.

00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:22.440
Because again,
we're getting back

00:49:22.440 --> 00:49:25.330
to the legal essence of a stock.

00:49:25.330 --> 00:49:27.950
It's part ownership
of the company.

00:49:27.950 --> 00:49:31.350
You're not actually betting--
there was that marketplace that

00:49:31.350 --> 00:49:33.570
got shot down online,
where you could back

00:49:33.570 --> 00:49:35.900
from different things,
maybe even things

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.720
like that-- how many iPhones
are going to get sold,

00:49:38.720 --> 00:49:41.590
and if they sold above
a certain number,

00:49:41.590 --> 00:49:42.900
you could actually get paid.

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:44.940
Well, that's not
what stocks are.

00:49:44.940 --> 00:49:47.340
Stocks are just ownership
in the business.

00:49:47.340 --> 00:49:51.910
So if you're fine with
10%, and you're fine

00:49:51.910 --> 00:49:55.660
with it growing very slowly,
you're going to make money.

00:49:55.660 --> 00:49:58.740
The market may expect
it to grow faster,

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:01.955
but that's not going to
take away your 10% yield.

00:50:05.300 --> 00:50:06.950
It does get
dangerous when you're

00:50:06.950 --> 00:50:10.690
buying very expensive
stocks, because there

00:50:10.690 --> 00:50:15.460
your yield from the business
is so low that you really

00:50:15.460 --> 00:50:18.370
are betting on something
great happening.

00:50:18.370 --> 00:50:21.710
And that's where
outsmarting the market

00:50:21.710 --> 00:50:23.270
becomes much more important.

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:24.900
But if you're just
sticking with things

00:50:24.900 --> 00:50:26.960
that you're totally
comfortable with,

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:28.510
you don't need to
worry very much

00:50:28.510 --> 00:50:30.615
about what the
market is predicting.

